comment:
Here's the problem: people were so conclusive before knowing the entirety of what happened between Heard and Depp, and the whole story still hasn't been revealed. Enough has been revealed now, I think, to take a side. But before people took the claims of JD being a "wife-beater" and stuck to it because that is an allegation that is easy to toss around for some people. In today's world, people no longer look into anything, they don't do background research, they just see an article online and believe the headlines, or the shallow, one-sided commentary within the article. Though it seems things are getting better for Depp, it doesn't change the fact that on multiple occasions this man has lost a lot. He's been excluded from roles, black-listed, losing money, losing unjustly in court, etc. By the way, I want to mention now, the ruling of the UK Court case HAS BEEN ALTERED. The way it reads now is different from how it read when it was first released. The original ruling was that the article in question, where The Sun labeled Johnny Depp a "wife-beater", was found to be "Substantially accurate on the balance of probabilities." The simplified version of that ruling is: Johnny (Depp) was rightfully labeled a 'wife-beater' on the grounds that we believe it is possible that Depp could be abusive." 

Quite honestly, removing Depp from the Disney brand, especially one of his most notable roles, was a business move on the part of Disney. It's hard to swallow if you are a fan of Depp, but you have to understand that the move is something Disney had to make in order to be safe with their product. In the chance Depp was/is abusive, it would look bad for Disney to keep him on board and be associated with supporting him. That's just business. I think it was disgusting for him to be cast out of many things before the details are known, but that's just corporate pandering, which is also why Hollywood is considered "progressive". 

However, if Disney still decides to move forward with a "progressive", female-led Pirates of the Caribbean, this could've also been a move to make it happen. Obviously, if you're wanting to change the series drastically by moving forward with new characters and new dynamics, you have to first rid yourself of anything to do with the original. But this is just speculation. 

If they're truly sorry, they can make it up to him with future work, but honestly, if I were Depp, I'd wipe my hands clean with the Pirates franchise as it seems to be making moves towards new waters, no pun intended.

comment: I dont see how it's being affliated with someone just because they have problems whether it is true or not.  People lose their jobs, reputation and more because of accusations, allegations, etc and even proven innocent, lack of proof, the damage is done.  You cannot fix that.  No apologies can either.  And you can't just go gack to the way it was before that especially when one is still looked at and treated like they have done wrong.  People still treat you like you have.  They keep checking you out, giving you another look or checking you out.  This sort of thing ruins not only the individual but their families too even to the point of moving or starting over.  It's one thing if found guilty and jail/prison time obviously they won't be coming to work.  And just because one isnt fired doesnt mean the business, franchise etc is ok with it.  There is a difference between business and personal.  Unfortunately lots cannot separate the two.  When say tv actors are fired before proven they have committed crime that is like being tried and convicted before going to court, arrested etc.  It's  putting the cart before the horse.  It makes nonsense to me.  I can speak of this sort of thing on experience on more than one occassion.  Not all rumors and accusations are true but lots believe the accuser or the one that runs their mouth first just based on their word or because they said something first.   Then the other has to prove no wrong doing or has to clean up the big mess the other has made.

comment: If Captain Jack Sparrow'Johhny Depp is the main figure in any future Pirates of the Caribbean movies, I will whole heartedly not only go to see them once, but several times each...... and my pirates collection of merchandise will surely swell!   Kudos to Disney, if they DID Listen to the fans - but please, drop the 'female pirates lead figure' nonsense.    Pirates fans don't want to see that  as some prominent character.   Put more women in the crew if you must, but leave our Captain Jack as we like him - as Captain of the Black Pearl.   Go have him find a way to raid Atlantis to find some artifact, or have him talking to sea serpents to defeat some awful  other ruthless pirate, or even have him running around the volcano on Monserrate or around , over and through the alligator filled swamps around New Orleans, but keep the female pirates as sideline characters at best.   Not a one of us will be going to watch them anyway!     It's Captain Jack we pay to go see and unless Johnny Depp wants to pass the character on to another actor, we want to see HIM playing that part.    Sean Connery aged as he played various adventurous parts, and so can our favorite pirate captain!   it was the 'charming, mischievous rogue who could outwit anyone ' that so firmly endeared himself to us.    Let Captain Jack be that again!   Quit trying to make him into some bottom of the barrel lowlife who doesn't care anymore, as You've been trying to do for years now.   We love Captain Jack Sparrow, especially as he first came to us - outlandish, bold, brave, cunning, clever, quick witted, and cool!!!!!    All it took was the audio tapes to prove what a framing job Amber Heard has been doing on this guy.   I hope you DID apologize.   You certainly owe Mr. Depp one.

comment:
Honestly I wouldn't be surprised if this had nothing to do with the actual contents of the case. Disney and Warner Bros have been competitors for a long time. Swooping in to save the fan favorite while Warner Bros is stuck with the perpetrator sets Warner up to fail because since they also fired the fan favorite. So Warner Bros will be seen as a collaborator in his abuse, losing them possibly hundreds of thousands of fans (customers). Disney may be doing this intentionally to get Warner Bros cornered in a buy-out deal. (I wouldn't be surprised if Disney and Warner had an agreement to black list him)
But for what it's worth- I'm glad Johnny is benefiting from this. When you have an abuser brag so loudly that their victim will never be supported, change is needed in our whole society. Hopefully this whole affair will make victims of abuse more able to find help irregardless of sex.
